Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1861, the first military action to earn a Medal of Honor occurred.

During the U.S.-Apache conflict, Colonel Bernard J.D. Irwin, an assistant army surgeon, volunteered to rescue Second Lieutenant George N. Bascom, who was trapped by the Apaches near Arizona. Irwin led 14 men on a 100-mile journey, initially without horses, and managed to break the siege by capturing Apaches and recovering stolen livestock. 

This conflict had started when Apache chief Cochise kidnapped a young boy. Although Irwin's heroic actions occurred during the conflict, the Medal of Honor was not established until 1862, and Irwin received it in 1894.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
Yesterday, I proudly stood alongside @RepPressley  as she reintroduced H.R. 40, the bill to establish a federal commission to study and develop reparations proposals for Black Americans. This fight for justice has been generations in the making, and I am honored to carry forward the legacy of Congressman John Conyers and Congresswoman Sheila Jackson Lee, who championed this legislation for decades.

For over 400 years, Black Americans have faced systemic racial oppression‚Äîfrom slavery to Jim Crow to present-day disparities in wealth, housing, healthcare, and education. H.R. 40 isn‚Äôt just about studying history‚Äîit‚Äôs about ensuring our nation finally reckons with its past and takes steps toward restorative justice.

Reparations are not a radical idea‚Äîthey are a moral and economic necessity. The racial wealth gap remains staggering: White households hold nearly 10 times the wealth of Black households, and systemic discrimination in housing, lending, and education continues to this day.

I fully support H.R. 40 because America must acknowledge and address the harm it has inflicted. Justice demands action. Grateful to my colleagues who continue this fight.

Name: Nehls, Troy E.
text: Private universities may be the most tax-exempt organizations in America. They earn millions by investing the tax-deductible donations they receive from alumni. They pay no taxes on the income they receive from tuition, fees, royalties, ticket sales, and TV broadcast rights. Most universities pay no local property taxes and can tap tax-exempt municipal bonds to fund their expansion.

Name: Nehls, Troy E.
text: Princeton‚Äôs 2022 990 tax return form shows that the university booked $3.6 billion in total revenues but received more in government grants ($406 million) than in charitable donations ($354 million). Charitable donations compose less than 10% of the university‚Äôs income. How can Princeton call itself a charity when so little of its income comes from charitable donations?

Name: Nehls, Troy E.
text: It is easy to see why some people are so worried about the tax on Princeton‚Äôs endowment; nearly half of the university‚Äôs income in 2022 ($1.7 billion) was in the form of investment income. Princeton has become a trust fund baby.

Name: Nehls, Troy E.
text: Princeton is a glaring example of why this system should be reformed. Princeton has been earning almost 10% annually on its endowment for the past decade but pays out only 5% toward scholarships and operations. No wonder the endowment keeps growing.

Name: Nehls, Troy E.
text: While Princeton is growing its endowment, it has also been busy tapping into tax-exempt municipal bonds. Why draw down on an endowment that is earning 10% annually when you can borrow at a rate less than 5% using taxpayer-subsidized bonds? Some might characterize this as arbitrage, which municipal bonds prohibit.

Name: Nehls, Troy E.
text: If every retiree must pay tax on the investment returns when they draw down their 401k, it‚Äôs only fair that large university endowments pay tax on their lucrative investment gains.

Name: Nehls, Troy E.

President Trump‚Äôs stoppage of U.S. foreign aid has halted land mine removal programs across the world‚Äîplacing regional security and the safety of American military personnel at risk. As a member of the House Unexploded Ordnance/Demining Caucus, I am proud to introduce H.R. 1259, the Global Demining Protection Act‚Äîlegislation to require the Trump Administration to immediately resume worldwide demining activities in the interest of U.S. national security. Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Since Russia‚Äôs war in Ukraine started, American deterrence and leadership have been at stake. That actually matters a lot‚Äîunless you want to re-enter the pre-WWII era of human history. Luckily, Trump‚Äôs leadership is changing the equation in Ukraine. As I‚Äôve long argued, there‚Äôs an opportunity here now. With mounting Russian casualties and Trump‚Äôs willingness to impose tougher sanctions, leverage increases. Strength forces tough choices, and Putin knows he‚Äôs out of options. If we want this war to end on our terms, we also need to give him an off-ramp that secures stability without endless war. This is a delicate dance.

That‚Äôs why Secretary Hegseth is right‚Äîconcessions will have to be made, which the Ukrainians know as well. We aren‚Äôt handing Putin a victory. Putin only achieves victory if he takes Ukraine and its capital. Instead, we‚Äôre forcing him into a deal that stops the bloodshed and strengthens our position for the long term.

‚ÄúWinning‚Äù for America is simple: we must re-establish deterrence, and you do that by making Putin (and others like him) regret their decision to break 80 years of global norms and engage in a war of conquest. How do you know he regrets it? When he comes to the table to negotiate. The details of that settlement matter a lot less than many people think.

On Jan 1, 2025, a 2.83% Medicare reimbursement cut took effect, compounding rising practice costs to an unsustainable 6.43% cut. Medicare physician reimbursement has dropped 33% since 2001, forcing layoffs, reduced services, and closures‚Äîespecially in rural and underserved areas.

As a proud cosponsor of HR 879‚Äîthe Medicare Patient Access and Practice Stabilization Act‚Äî I‚Äôm fighting to stop these cuts and protect seniors‚Äô access to care. This bipartisan bill prevents further cuts, provides a modest inflationary adjustment, and ensures Medicare remains viable for both doctors and patients.

Medicare beneficiaries deserve quality care, not barriers. We must protect seniors‚Äô access to care and support the providers who make it possible.

Name: Hill, J. French
text:
Martha and I are saddened to learn of the passing of former Governor Jim Guy Tucker.

Governor Tucker served as my predecessor in the U.S. House of Representatives from the Second Congressional District from 1977 to 1979.

During that time, he was a kind and thoughtful mentor to me during my high school and college years. During his time as our governor, we collaborated on the design and construction of the beautiful new visitor center at the Historic Arkansas Museum, known then as the Arkansas Territorial Restoration.

Over the years, it was such a pleasure to see him, share my experiences in Congress, and seek his advice. Martha and I extend our condolences and prayers for comfort to Betty and the entire family. Arkansas has lost a great advocate.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
üö® REP. ROY STATEMENT ON BUDGET RESOLUTION üö®

‚ÄúToday I voted to report the Chairman‚Äôs FY25 Budget Resolution out of the Budget Committee. I did so with reservations due to the urgency of our current debt crisis and my concern that there is insufficient resolve in Congress to address that crisis, thus leaving Americans with the devastating tax of inflation and high interest rates.  Yet the bill would ‚Äî if adopted by Republicans on the House floor ‚Äî represent an historic level of spending reductions paired with extension and expansion of President Trump‚Äôs tax policies and would take a significant step down the path to fiscal sanity while simultaneously delivering on critical portions of President Trump's agenda.

It was not easy to reach this point. My Budget Committee colleagues ‚Äî along with support from the House Freedom Caucus ‚Äî had to push hard to achieve the spending cuts included in this resolution. We did what members of Congress are supposed to do: we deliberated, negotiated, and legislated. Chairman Jodey Arrington deserves particular compensation for standing strong and showing true leadership and resilience during this process.

What we achieved through those talks is a plan to do what the American people want it to do: cut wasteful spending and keep taxes low. Today's budget resolution will enable us to reach $4.5 trillion in tax cuts and potentially more than $2 trillion in spending cuts over ten years.

While I believe we should be able to do far better than a mere annual $200 Billion of reductions on over $7 trillion in total annual spending, the bill will supplement Elon Musk‚Äôs and DOGE's mission to eradicate government waste, and it lays the foundation to fully unleash the Trump economic agenda. Further, this plan takes away Chuck Schumer and Senate Democrats' ability to hold the economy hostage by raising the debt ceiling coupled with reducing spending.

Most urgently, this sets us up to rush $300 billion in funding for border security, immigration enforcement and the military so those critical missions continue uninterrupted.

The American people expect us to deliver and we have a duty to do what we said. Today's resolution is an important part of doing so.  Onward.‚Äù

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1990, the Voyager 1 spacecraft, 3.7 billion miles from the sun, captured an iconic photograph of Earth, known as the "Pale Blue Dot." 

Launched in 1977, Voyager 1 was tasked with exploring the outer solar system. After passing Jupiter and Saturn, Voyager 1 continued its journey, reaching Neptune a decade later. From there, it captured a series of images, known as the "Family Portrait," with Pale Blue Dot being the most famous. In the image, Earth appears as a tiny speck, barely visible, about the size of a pixel. 

In 1998, it became the most distant human-made object in space, and in 2012, it crossed into interstellar space, leaving the sun's magnetic field and solar winds behind.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
It‚Äôs a lie to say that Dems are ‚Äúfighting for‚Äù waste, fraud, and abuse. Every single tax dollar ought to be spent efficiently and wisely. Nobody is debating that. Here‚Äôs what we are debating:

1) Elon keeps crying "waste" but it's really just things he doesn‚Äôt like.
¬†
2) We don't live in a dictatorship. The Constitution gives Congress the power of the purse. Republicans have a majority in both Houses. Congress‚Äîwhich is elected by you, the people, to do this job‚Äîshould debate these ideas and pass them into law in full daylight and transparency. The way Elon is doing things is sketchy and unconstitutional.

3) Why did Elon and Trump fire all the independent, nonpartisan Inspectors General who investigate and shut down waste, fraud and abuse?
¬†
4) And on that note, why didn‚Äôt they start by sending DOGE to the Pentagon, which is the *biggest* part of discretionary federal spending, and has never passed an audit? Instead they chose to dismantle an agency that passed an audit three months ago‚Ä¶

5) It appears Elon gets a lot of money from Pentagon contracts. Is he acting corruptly? Does he have a conflict of interest?

6) We can‚Äôt be sure, because he‚Äôs not filing a financial disclosure form like every other senior official has to do! Where‚Äôs the transparency?
¬†
6) His focus is on cutting programs that help people‚Äîinstead of talking about why so many billionaires don‚Äôt pay what they owe in taxes. Maybe we wouldn't have to cut so much if big corporations just paid their taxes? Would be a great debate to have in Congress!

Dems are fighting because we believe that what Elon is doing will hurt a lot of people in this country.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share the remarkable stories of those who have shaped our community through their courage, service, and sacrifice. Today, we recognize a man whose life is not just part of history but has helped define it. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: World War II Veteran Chuck Kunes of Middletown, the last surviving member of the legendary Black Sheep Squadron, who turns 100 years young on February 27th.
 
In 1942, at only 18 years old and the world at war, Chuck bravely stepped forward and proudly answered the call to serve. He enlisted in the United States Marine Corps and became part of VMF-214, the Black Sheep Squadron‚Äîone of the most revered aviation units in military history. Under the fearless leadership of Major Gregory "Pappy" Boyington, Chuck and his squadron took part in some of the fiercest air battles of the Pacific. As a flight mechanic, his role was vital‚Äîensuring that warplanes were combat-ready, that pilots could return to the skies, and that the fight for freedom would endure. The Black Sheep Squadron became legends, and Chuck stood among them‚Äîa young man whose quiet courage and unshakable resolve helped turn the tide of history.
 
When the war ended, Chuck returned home and became one of the original residents of the Stony Brook section of Levittown. Here, he helped shape one of the most special communities in our district‚Äîa community where veterans and families built their futures, bound together by the resilience and camaraderie of a generation that had sacrificed so much. For over 40 years, Chuck served as an executive at 3M in Bristol, leading with the same integrity, discipline, and steadfast commitment that had defined his service. His greatest achievement, however, is in the life he built. Alongside his beloved wife, Alma, they raised three wonderful children, instilling the same values of service, sacrifice, and love of community and country.
 
I had the profound honor of celebrating Chuck on his 96th birthday and paying tribute to his extraordinary service in Washington last April. Now, as he nears his 100th birthday, please join me in honoring a life that epitomizes duty, valor, and selfless service. Happy 100th Birthday, Chuck! Our community and our nation will forever be indebted to your inspiring legacy.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
Today, I introduced the Secure Rural Schools Reauthorization Act. For rural counties, Secure Rural Schools funding is essential. This program ensures that schools stay open, roads are maintained, and emergency services are available, even when federal timber revenues fall short.

In 2024 alone, California received $33.7 million through this program‚Äîfunding that helps keep classrooms running and supports vital services like public safety and infrastructure. These funds replace the lost timber tax receipts that local governments once relied on. Without this funding, rural areas would struggle to provide even the most basic services. This is the same administration that pulled the U.S. out of the World Health Organization and the same President who once suggested injecting bleach as treatment for COVID-19. We cannot afford to stand by as the Trump administration dismantles our public health system, leaving Americans vulnerable and putting lives on the line. Their reckless policies threaten to cripple the very infrastructure we rely on to prevent disease outbreaks, respond to health emergencies, and ensure access to care. The safety and well-being of our families should never be bartered away for political gains or billionaire tax breaks. Last year, I announced $1,000,000 in Community Project Funding that I helped secure for the construction of the Zapata County Emergency Operations Center (EOC). This new state-of-the-art, centralized facility will provide Zapata County‚Äôs first responders, fire department, and emergency services with the resources they need to enhance coordination and improve emergency response times for local residents.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First: 

Dr. LaToya McCurdy, DNP, FNP-BC, a healthcare leader from Rocky Mount, NC, is dedicated to improving her community's well-being. She founded NEWH Regional Medical Center in 2022, which provided essential primary care services across Nash, Edgecombe, Wilson, and Halifax counties. Dr. McCurdy also founded the Jamcha Foundation, Inc., which focuses on improving health outcomes, especially among underrepresented communities in eastern North Carolina.
Beyond her healthcare practice, Dr. McCurdy plays a vital role in shaping the next generation of healthcare professionals. As an adjunct faculty member at NC Wesleyan University, she educates students and fosters leadership in the field.

Her public service has earned national recognition, including honors from the American Association of Nurse Practitioners for her leadership during the COVID-19 pandemic. Her work inspires and empowers her community and future healthcare leaders.

Dr. McCurdy's dedication shows that one person can spark real change, proving that investing in others elevates the entire community.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
Dozens of Alaskans ‚Äì potentially over 100 in total ‚Äì are being fired as part of the Trump administration‚Äôs reduction-in-force order for the federal government.
¬†
Many of these abrupt terminations will do more harm than good, stunting opportunities in Alaska and leaving holes in our communities. We can‚Äôt realize our potential for responsible energy and mineral development if we can‚Äôt permit projects. We will be less prepared to manage summer wildfires if we can‚Äôt support those on the front lines. Our tourism economy will be damaged if we don‚Äôt maintain our world-class national parks and forests.¬†
¬†
I share the administration‚Äôs goal of reducing the size of the federal government, but this approach is bringing confusion, anxiety, and now trauma to our civil servants‚Äîsome of whom moved their families and packed up their whole lives to come here. Indiscriminate workforce cuts aren‚Äôt efficient and won‚Äôt fix the federal budget, but they will hurt good people who have answered the call to public service to do important work for our nation.
¬†
My staff and I are in close touch with agency and department officials, trying to get answers about the impact of these terminations. Our goal is to forestall unnecessary harm‚Äîfor people and Alaska‚Äôs federal priorities‚Äîbut the response so far has been evasive and inadequate.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1998, racing legend Dale Earnhardt Sr. finally won his first Daytona 500, NASCAR's season opener. 

Earnhardt, known as ‚ÄúThe Intimidator,‚Äù became a dominant force in NASCAR, with 76 career victories and seven championships, tying the record held by Richard Petty and Jimmie Johnson. However, victory at the Daytona 500 eluded him until 1998, despite a series of close calls, including a frightening crash in the 1997 race. 

Earnhardt died in a crash during the Daytona 500 in 2001, just three years after his memorable win. Three years later, his son, Dale Jr., won his first Daytona 500.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
I agree with many people, including Vice President JD Vance, who believe that at the end of this conflict Ukraine must be standing as a sovereign, independent nation. The Ukrainians have fought like tigers and have a lot to be proud of. 

However, it is not helpful to suggest that Ukraine needs to enter NATO because Putin is planning to take over Europe. 

If Putin plans to take over Europe, clearly he is not intimidated by NATO. I believe very strongly that Putin wants no part of a war with NATO because it would be the end of Putin‚Äôs Russia.  

My proposal to deter Putin is simple: Learn from the mistakes of 2014. 

1. Arm Ukraine by selling them American weapons over the next decade to prevent future Russian military incursions.

2. Pursue economic integration between Ukraine and the U.S. that would be financially beneficial to both countries and would create a new relationship to counter Russia. 

3. While there is a debate as to whether Ukraine should be in NATO now, let‚Äôs make it clear to Putin that if there is a third invasion, Ukraine would be automatically admitted into NATO. 

All these proposals together create deterrence and prevents future and wider conflicts.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.

One year ago, Alexei Navalny was murdered because he refused to surrender‚Äîto corruption, to tyranny, to the fear that keeps so many silent. He stood for democracy in a nation where speaking truth is a death sentence. He was jailed, beaten, poisoned‚Äîand still, he fought on.

Putin may have ended Navalny‚Äôs life, but he could not erase his defiance. He could not undo the courage Navalny inspired in millions. History does not bend to dictators; it bends to those who dare to change it.

In Navalny‚Äôs honor, I led the effort to rename the street outside the Russian Ambassador‚Äôs residence Alexei Navalny Way‚Äîa permanent mark of resistance in the heart of our nation‚Äôs capitol‚Äîbecause America must always stand with those who fight for freedom, whether in Russia, in Ukraine, or anywhere tyranny seeks to tighten its grip.

Navalny‚Äôs story did not end in a prison cell. His fight is now ours‚Äîto remember, to honor, and to continue.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1801, Thomas Jefferson was elected as the third president of the United States.

Jefferson had significant political experience, having drafted the Declaration of Independence and served in various roles including minister to France, Secretary of State under George Washington, and vice president under John Adams. 

After a bitter campaign, Jefferson and Aaron Burr ended up tied with 73 electoral votes each, while Adams received 65. Federalist leader Alexander Hamilton influenced the House to vote against Burr, ultimately securing Jefferson‚Äôs victory. Jefferson became president and Burr vice president.

Happy Presidents Day!

The most remarkable thing about George Washington was not that he was our first President, the Commander in Chief of the Continental Army, and the President of the Constitutional Convention.

The most remarkable thing about George Washington was that after all of his accomplishments, after 8 years as President, and while he enjoyed enormous admiration from the people and the military...he gave it up! 

No one had done that before. Kings and Queens would hand over their thrones to spouses, children, or siblings. No one had simply left it up to the people. That is the greatness of Washington and America!

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy

I honor Washington's brave contributions to our nation's founding and the legacy of the many presidents who have followed in his footsteps, leading our great country with courage, strength, and integrity. I am grateful to those Presidents who upheld our Constitution, so America can be prosperous, safe, and free.

When Washington‚Äôs officers wanted to make him King, he refused and said, ‚ÄúThe Army must serve the country, but not rule it. Express your utmost horror and detestation of the man who wished to overturn the liberties of our country.‚Äù

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text: Happy Presidents‚Äô Day to all those that are working today and all those that are lucky enough not to be working today. Enjoy this Presidents‚Äô Day as it is an exclusively American day, during which we honor the presidency, the Constitution, and the Separation of Powers, laid out in Article I, Article II, and Article III. The Executive Powers are established by Article II. Followed and enforced by the father of our country, George Washington, while president, forbade anyone from ever referring to him as anything more than Mr. President ‚Äî there were no ‚Äúyour highnesses‚Äù within earshot of George Washington. There were many predictions around the world that our first president George Washington would not leave the office, but he did quite willingly, quite voluntarily, while his countryman pleaded with him to remain. We have a great country and great people. We are a lasting constitutional republic‚Ä¶ ‚ÄúIf we can keep it,‚Äù in the words of Benjamin Franklin, a great Founding Father and Pennsylvanian. Washington, and thankfully, all of our Founders, were completely determined to form a government by the people and for the people. There is a desire today, probably has always been by some, to change so that we have a government that rules the people‚Ä¶ this will not stand in America. The people will rule the government‚Ä¶ that‚Äôs America. Let‚Äôs all resolve to do our part for our families and for all American families to keep America‚Ä¶ America. Happy President‚Äôs Day.

Name: Neal, Richard E.
text:
The first Presidents' Day was celebrated in 1879 as a tribute to George Washington. Despite the overwhelming adoration he received, President Washington recognized the importance of setting a precedent to prevent the kind of tyranny he fought to subvert. He gave up his power and ultimately observed the first peaceful transfer of power in our nation's history.

On this Presidents' Day, we thank those leaders like Washington who led with great honor, courage, compassion, and integrity, who understood the significance of the office and our democratic institutions, and were grateful for the honor and privilege of working on behalf of the American people.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
Based on your comments which I fully appreciate and don‚Äôt disagree with, I‚Äôll share more information about serving in Congress.
For the yellow weeks, when we are in session, we have to fly into DC from our districts so that is a full travel day for many of us.
The last day of the week we fly back home to our districts, another full travel day. At least for those of us who don‚Äôt live in Washington. I do not live in Washington DC, I live in my district.
When we are not in session, we are either working at our district offices, meeting with constituents in our districts, or traveling. 
Most of us also have families that we don‚Äôt get to spend enough time with.
We also have to afford two homes, one in DC and one in our districts. Unlike some, I don‚Äôt sleep in my office. 
We are Representatives and our constituent services work is what you don‚Äôt see on tv and takes place back in our districts, but is actually some of most important work we do.
Lastly, we in the House don‚Äôt vote on President Trump‚Äôs nominations. The Senate only confirms nominations.
If I could change anything, I would require Congress to pass a balanced budget every year or not be qualified to run for re-election. 
For example, if the 119th Congress can‚Äôt balance the budget, then the entire Congress gets replaced the next election.
But I think I‚Äôm pretty alone in Congress in that opinion.
But what do y‚Äôall think?

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1924, Secretary of the Navy Edwin Denby resigns as a result of the Teapot Dome scandal.

Early in the Harding administration, Secretary of the Navy Edwin Denby convinced President Harding to transfer control of Navy oil reserves to the Department of the Interior. Secretary Albert B. Fall secretly leased these reserves to oilmen Harry F. Sinclair and Edward L. Doheny without competitive bidding. 

An investigation revealed Fall received over $400,000 in "loans" for his help. The leases were canceled, and Fall was convicted of bribery, becoming the first cabinet member jailed for crimes in office. Sinclair and Doheny were acquitted, but Sinclair was later convicted of contempt. Harding wasn't directly involved but faced criticism for poor cabinet choices and lack of oversight.

It‚Äôs Black History Month, and today we‚Äôre celebrating Newark native and hip-hop legend, Queen Latifah.

Queen Latifah grew up in the East Orange area, and began beat-boxing with Ladies Fresh and the Unit after high school. In her music career, Queen Latifah challenged Eurocentric standards of beauty and made music about the struggles Black women face.

In addition to pioneering female rap, she starred on the sitcom ‚ÄòLiving Single‚Äô which highlighted the Black American experience of the 90s.

Queen Latifah was the first hip-hop artist to receive a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame, and continues to be a pillar in her home state of New Jersey.

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Today, as I continue to celebrate Black History Month, I am highlighting the incredible legacy of West Chester local Horace Pippin, a decorated World War I veteran, artist, and civil rights activist. During the war, Pippin served in the then-segregated U.S. Army as part of the all-Black Harlem Hellfighters infantry regiment. At the Battle of Sechault, Pippin was shot and later awarded the Purple Heart for his valor. After the war, he pursued his passion for art, creating pieces mixing his experiences as a soldier and a black man in segregated America. His works brought attention to the plight of African Americans and explored artistic avenues for resisting oppression during the civil rights movement. His pieces received national acclaim and have been displayed in the MoMa, the Philadelphia Museum of Art, and the National Gallery of Art. I am thankful for his service to our country, his transformative contributions to our nation's artistic legacy, and his enduring advocacy for civil rights.

(The second photo is his painting of the West Chester Court House!)

Name: Clyburn, James E.
text:
#BlackHistoryMonth The Honorable Matthew Perry, Jr. was a remarkable civil rights attorney who made history as the first African American U.S. District Court judge for South Carolina.

The first time I saw Matthew Perry, my mother brought me to watch him argue a case for the NAACP. Though I would come to know him in many roles ‚Äî from mentor to fraternity brother ‚Äî I will never forget the awe I felt sitting in the Sumter Courthouse that day.

A native of Columbia, SC, Judge Perry played a pivotal role in nearly every case that led to integration in South Carolina, representing Sarah Mae Flemming, Harvey Gantt, and countless others in their lawsuits seeking justice and equality. Through his work, he helped shape a new era of opportunity, leaving a lasting impact not only on South Carolina, but on the entire nation.
